# GitHub Actions: Performance and Testing

## Caching

- Use `actions/cache` (pinned to a full commit SHA) for dependencies and build outputs.
- Design cache keys with `hashFiles()` so the cache invalidates only when relevant files change.
- Use `restore-keys` for graceful fallback to older compatible caches.

### Example — monorepo Node cache

```yaml
- name: Cache Node.js modules
  uses: actions/cache@668228422ae6a00e4ad889ee87cd7109ec5666a7 # v5.0.4
  with:
    path: |
      ~/.npm
      ./node_modules
    key: ${{ runner.os }}-node-${{ hashFiles('**/package-lock.json') }}-${{ github.run_id }}
    restore-keys: |
      ${{ runner.os }}-node-${{ hashFiles('**/package-lock.json') }}-
      ${{ runner.os }}-node-
```

## Matrix strategies

- Use `strategy.matrix` to run jobs in parallel across versions, OSes, or browsers.
- Use `include`/`exclude` to fine-tune combinations.
- Use `fail-fast: true` (default) for quick failure feedback, or `fail-fast: false` when you want comprehensive test results.

### Example — multi-version, multi-OS test matrix

```yaml
jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ${{ matrix.os }}
    strategy:
      fail-fast: false
      matrix:
        os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest]
        node-version: [16.x, 18.x, 20.x]
        browser: [chromium, firefox]
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@34e114876b0b11c390a56381ad16ebd13914f8d5 # v4.3.1
      - uses: actions/setup-node@3235b876344d2a9aa001b8d1453c930bba69e610 # v3.9.1
        with:
          node-version: ${{ matrix.node-version }}
      - run: npx playwright install ${{ matrix.browser }}
      - run: npm test
```

## Checkout optimization

- Default to `fetch-depth: 1` for `actions/checkout` — most jobs don't need full history.
- Only use `fetch-depth: 0` when explicitly required (release tagging, `git blame`, deep commit analysis).
- Skip submodules (`submodules: false`) and LFS when not required.

## Artifacts

- Use `actions/upload-artifact` and `actions/download-artifact` (pinned SHAs) to pass large payloads between jobs.
- Set `retention-days` deliberately to control storage costs.
- Upload test reports (JUnit XML, HTML, coverage) and deployment artifacts for inspection and historical trend analysis.

## Self-hosted runners

- Use only when GitHub-hosted runners don't meet needs (GPU, on-prem access, very high volume).
- Harden runner machines, manage access, patch promptly, and restrict network egress.
- Use runner groups to organize and assign runners by purpose or environment.

