## Testing strategy

### Unit tests

- Run on every push and PR. They should be fast and numerous.
- Parallelize aggressively (via matrix or test runner sharding).
- Publish JUnit XML / coverage reports as artifacts and surface them via GitHub Checks.
- Track code coverage and enforce a minimum threshold — focus on meaningful tests, not just line count.

### Integration tests

- Use `services:` blocks to spin up databases, queues, or caches as ephemeral containers.
- Run after unit tests, before E2E.
- Plan for test data setup/teardown to keep runs repeatable.

### End-to-end tests

- Use Playwright, Cypress, or Selenium for realistic browser flows.
- Prefer running against a staging environment that mirrors production when feasible.
- Mitigate flakiness: explicit waits, stable selectors (`data-testid`), and retries for transient failures.
- Capture screenshots and video on failure for faster debugging.

### Performance and load tests

- Tools: k6, JMeter, Locust, Gatling, Artillery.
- Run less frequently than unit/integration tests (nightly, weekly, or on release branches).
- Define thresholds (latency, throughput, error rate) and fail the build when they regress.

### Reporting and visibility

- Surface test results as GitHub Checks/annotations for inline PR feedback.
- Upload comprehensive reports (JUnit XML, HTML, coverage, screenshots, videos) as artifacts.
- Consider external dashboards (SonarQube, Allure, TestRail) for historical trends.
- Add workflow status badges to README for at-a-glance CI health.

## Performance/testing review checklist

- [ ] `actions/cache` used for package manager deps and large build outputs.
- [ ] Cache keys use `hashFiles()` and have `restore-keys` fallbacks.
- [ ] Parallelism via `strategy.matrix` where it makes sense.
- [ ] `fetch-depth: 1` on `actions/checkout` unless full history is required.
- [ ] Artifacts used for inter-job data transfer with appropriate `retention-days`.
- [ ] Unit tests run early on every push/PR.
- [ ] Integration tests run with `services:` for real dependencies.
- [ ] E2E tests run against staging with retries and failure artifacts captured.
- [ ] Performance tests run on a schedule with defined thresholds.
- [ ] Test reports uploaded and surfaced via GitHub Checks.
- [ ] Coverage tracked and enforced at a minimum threshold.
